WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.192
On its own, gamma-P-G-A is a floppy tangle of chains that

2
00:00:03.292 --> 00:00:06.253
all carry a negative charge — so they repel and slide

3
00:00:06.353 --> 00:00:09.199
past each other. How do you turn that into a solid?

4
00:00:09.966 --> 00:00:13.909
Calcium is the answer. Each calcium ion carries two positive charges

5
00:00:14.009 --> 00:00:16.585
— so it can grab a negative site on one chain

6
00:00:16.685 --> 00:00:19.558
and a negative site on the next, at the same time.

7
00:00:19.633 --> 00:00:22.328
Each ion clamps two chains together into a bridge.

8
00:00:23.200 --> 00:00:27.516
How many bridges form? A binding curve tells us: as calcium rises, more

9
00:00:27.616 --> 00:00:31.746
sites get clamped, until the chains are saturated and it levels off.

10
00:00:33.433 --> 00:00:37.099
And bridge count is what sets stiffness. More clamps means a denser

11
00:00:37.199 --> 00:00:40.360
network — and a denser network is a stiffer, stronger gel.

12
00:00:42.633 --> 00:00:45.692
So the whole story is: count the calcium clamps, and that

13
00:00:45.792 --> 00:00:48.907
number becomes the stiffness the crust brings to the sand.

